In article <1992Apr21.171200.21262@cs.cornell.edu> wayner@cs.cornell.edu (Peter Wayner) writes:
> If 56 bits aren't enough, you can encrypt the data three times
>over with three different keys.

That's my preference.  However, I also prefer using CBC mode and prefixing
each of the three encryptions with 96 bits of truly random data.  This not
only adds more key-like information, it also offsets each of the DES blocks
from those of the previous round so that bits are further diffused.
